      "The VP explained the situation. A massive project nearly complete. Antivirus not yet deployed on the systems. If the launch happened without it, the whole thing could be stopped. Revenue impacted. Timeline blown. He needed this done, and he needed it done fast.",
      "My military-dependent brain processed his title before I processed the request. He was way up there. I was way down here. I grew up in a world where authority had physical presence — rank was visible, the hierarchy was clear, and your response to someone who outranked you was never really a question. That configuration was written years before I entered a corporate environment. It was still running, quietly, the moment a VP called.",
      "I didn't evaluate the request. I evaluated the source. And the source triggered an old rule: someone in authority has asked something of you, and your answer is yes. Not out of fear exactly — out of something that felt like responsibility, like competence, like the right thing to do. The urgency was already firing before I had finished listening to him explain the problem.",
      "This is what authority-triggered urgency does: it shortcircuits the evaluation layer. When something arrives with sufficient perceived authority — a title, a tone, a sense of consequence — the system bypasses the question of whether the request is reasonable and moves directly to execution. The urgency doesn't need to evaluate. It just needs a signal that the source is credible, and then it executes.",
      "In security, this is called social engineering. The attacker doesn't need to find a technical vulnerability in the system. They just need to find the person configured to say yes to authority and construct a request that looks like it comes from somewhere legitimate. The system does the rest. It's not a failure of intelligence. It's a feature of the configuration.",
