      "Identity-based rules are the hardest to examine because examining them feels like self-betrayal. If I question whether I should be the one solving this, am I questioning whether I'm still the fixer? If I say no, does that mean I'm no longer who I believed myself to be? The rule doesn't just govern behavior. It governs self-concept. Saying no to a request doesn't feel like a boundary. It feels like an identity failure.",
      "The cybersecurity equivalent is a user account that has accumulated permissions over years of legitimate requests. Each permission made sense when it was granted. Over time, the account has access to far more than any single role should have — not because of malicious intent, but because nothing was ever audited. The account isn't wrong. The accumulation is.",
      "I accumulated responsibilities the same way. Not because I grabbed them. Because I was configured to say yes, and yes kept building into more yes, and eventually the load was designed for an entire team being carried by one person who had convinced himself this was normal because the title said so. The fixer can fix anything. That's the rule. And the rule ran without question.",
      "My new manager saw exactly where I was. He saw the burnout through Zoom calls in a way I couldn't see it myself. 'Let's get you some help.' That sentence shifted my life. Not because it solved anything immediately, but because it interrupted the identity-based loop for long enough to ask whether the configuration still made sense.",
      "The fixer is still part of who I am. I still enjoy solving problems. I still help people navigate things they can't see from the inside. But I've learned the difference between operating from that identity and being consumed by it. The title can describe what I do without becoming the rule that decides what I must do next. That distinction is small and it is everything.",
