      "There is a concept in security called the illusion of coverage. A system appears protected because it once had redundancy built in. Over time, pieces fail or move on. The redundancy is gone. But nothing has announced the loss. The monitoring still shows green. The alerts are still quiet. The system still appears secure, right up until the moment it demonstrably isn't.",
      "I was running on the illusion of coverage for years. The system was functioning. Tickets closed. Projects landed. I could give an unscheduled presentation to a vice president on endpoint health without a hint of nerves. I was capable. I was also hollowed out in ways I couldn't name and wasn't measuring.",
      "What makes this hard to address is that performance is the thing everyone sees, and performance was continuing. I wasn't asking for help because I didn't know what help would mean. I was asking how much longer I could endure it — the wrong question entirely, but the only one the system was configured to ask.",
      "My manager saw it before I did. He noticed the burnout through Zoom calls over months of observation. He could see what I was hiding inside what looked like competence. That external perspective was the thing I couldn't provide for myself. When you're running on the illusion of not breaking, you don't have access to the view from outside. You're too busy maintaining the appearance.",
      "The question worth sitting with is not whether you're still functioning. Of course you are. That's how this works. The question is whether functioning and healthy mean the same thing for you right now — and whether you've checked recently or just assumed the answer was yes because nothing has visibly failed.",
