    title: "What Changed While You Were Surviving",
    hook: "You don't remember choosing this baseline. You remember surviving something. That's not the same thing.",
    pullQuote: "Baselines don't collapse. They drift. The emergency posture that was necessary in a hard season quietly becomes the normal posture — and keeps running long after the emergency resolves.",
    subhead: "On emergency configurations that outlasted their emergencies",
    body: [
      "Baselines don't collapse. They drift. There is no clear break point, no obvious failure, no moment that announces itself as the beginning of a different way of operating. What happens instead is slower and harder to detect. The emergency posture that was necessary in a hard season quietly becomes the normal posture. The tightened boundaries, the elevated alertness, the operating at full capacity as a default — these don't expire when the emergency does. They just keep running.",
      "I don't remember choosing to operate without margin. I remember surviving seasons that didn't leave room for it. I remember a stretch where the ticket queue never cleared, where the responsibility never lightened, where stepping back wasn't an option because there was no one to step back to. The way I moved through those seasons felt necessary. It was necessary. I was doing what the situation required.",
      "The situation changed. The workload eventually shifted. A new manager arrived. Things that had been impossible became possible. But the baseline didn't update automatically. I was still running the configuration I had built for a sustained crisis, inside conditions that no longer required it. Still scanning constantly. Still treating availability as non-negotiable. Still operating as if the original emergency was ongoing, even though the environment had changed entirely.",
      "In cybersecurity, there are systems still running security policies written during a breach response that occurred years ago. The breach was real. The response was appropriate. The policies were tightened, access was restricted, alerting was elevated. And then the incident closed. But no one updated the policies. The system kept running in incident-response mode because nothing ever signaled that the incident was over.",
      "Human systems do the same thing. The conditions that required the old baseline have often resolved or evolved. But the baseline remains because nothing announced the resolution. There was no ceremony. No clear signal that the emergency was over and you could stand down. The system just kept running in the posture it had learned to run in.",
      "This is why exhaustion so often feels confusing. You look at your current workload and it doesn't fully account for how you feel. The pressure doesn't seem new. Sometimes there's no actual overload in the queue. And yet your capacity feels thinner. Your patience shorter. Your recovery slower. That's because the strain isn't coming from what you're carrying now. It's coming from what you never put down.",
      "Recognizing this isn't self-pity. It's the beginning of an honest audit. Not everything that changed while you were surviving needs to be changed back. Some of what you built in hard seasons is real and good. But the first step toward choosing deliberately is being able to see what formed without being chosen — and asking whether it still makes sense in the environment you're actually in.",
    ],
    bookTie: "Chapter 16 of Unsecured is built around this pattern — the baseline that changed without being chosen and the survival settings that outlasted the emergencies that created them.",
